metadata.name: Cube on Cube #24
metadata.description:
This token generates a plottable SVG file, a different arrangement of cubes.
The cubes are designed in 2D view, then placed next to each other or on top of each other in eight different directions. The goal is to challenge the audience's mind to discover the holes or protrusions produced by placing the cubes together.
To produce random parts made of cubes, those in the same direction are merged together, which is a turning point in this project.
Do you need a different output from your piece?  Then use controllers!

Controllers 
G - Change light direction
F - Add/remove frame
L - Add/remove base lines
D - Change base lines direction
R - Reset to default settings
P - Save as PNG
S - Export high resolution SVG

Note : When you have a piece with many shapes, controllers may run delayed. (Depending on your device).

Made by p5.js

metadata.name: Angular View #23
metadata.description:
The angle factor plays a significant role in determining how an image feels and looks.
When viewed from one angle, elements inside the frame might appear compressed and unclear, while when viewed from another angle, they might appear clear and distinct.
Choosing the right angle can encourage and guide the audience, while choosing the wrong angle can confuse and mislead him.
Therefore, when choosing the angle, one should consider aesthetic, technical, and emotional factors to present the subject to the viewer in the best light.
Depending on the angle, space and subject of the image are transformed and they can convey various meanings, including: logical visualization of space/impossible and free visualization, exaggeration and exaggeration/simplicity, stillness/movement, insider/alienation, mysterious/reliable, and complexity.
Made by p5.js

metadata.name: Angular Waves #49
metadata.description:
Changes in viewing angle can reveal or postpone story information, introduce a specific location or mood, or create visual variety.
In fact, every angle of view alters the mood, rhythm, and even the fictional events in the space.
With changes in the viewing angle, the image's emotional and visual characteristics change, and with those changes, the implicit meaning of the work changes as well.
Viewing angles are affected by the visual experiences of everyday life, which contribute to their semantic load.
In the same way, what a person learns from his surroundings is stored in his mind and used to understand and interpret an image.
Made by p5.js

metadata.name: DÃ©collage #194
metadata.description:
A generative sketch based on the concept of dÃ©collage, an artistic process that involves cutting or tearing pieces of an original image. The resulting outputs bear a resemblance to artworks produced using the lacerated poster technique, where posters are layered and torn to reveal parts of the posters underneath.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels. Note that this will not work with sizes beyond 5000 pixels.

(Allowlist is based on quantity of previous works owned).

metadata.name: Texturism #103
metadata.description:
Before 2021, computational art was often associated with glitchy, flat, and motion visuals. However, with the emergence of generative art and fxhash, computational static painting has become the new aesthetic.

Texturism is an artwork that explores texture and color. By layering multiple strokes of colors, it aims to create an image with rich textures, embracing the intricate details in modern generative art paintings.
